<subSubSection id="3CD75DE6FFC3FFB4FF34E5A8FC6E3C90" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="74720E6DFFC3FFB4FF34E5A8FC6E3C90" blockId="10.[160,1156,697,931]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFC3FFB4FF34E5A8FEDE3DE0" bold="true" box="[160,282,697,723]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Females of 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFC3FFB4FE33E5ABFD913DE0" authorityName=": Raw" authorityYear="2007" box="[423,597,698,723]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rancaguensis">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFC3FFB4FE33E5ABFD913DE0" box="[423,597,698,723]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">M. rancaguensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are recognised by the long white vestiture all over the body. The hairs on the scutum are very long, up to 2.3× MOD. Males of 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFC3FFB4FC41E5CDFB473DC6" authorityName=": Raw" authorityYear="2007" box="[981,1155,732,757]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rancaguensis">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFC3FFB4FC41E5CDFB473DC6" box="[981,1155,732,757]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">M. rancaguensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are distinguished from those of 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFC3FFB4FD92E5EEFD5E3C2B" box="[518,666,767,792]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucografa">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFC3FFB4FD92E5EEFD5E3C2B" box="[518,666,767,792]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">M. leucografa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFC3FFB4FD46E5EEFC9C3C2B" authorityName=": Raw" authorityYear="2007" box="[722,856,767,792]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscurior">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFC3FFB4FD46E5EEFC9C3C2B" box="[722,856,767,792]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">M. obscurior</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the last flagellomere of the antenna, which is not broadened, the usually reduced group of short ferruginous setae on the forecoxa (5–7 setae up to 0.33× MOD), and the longer pubescence all over the body, the hairs on the scutum being up to 2.7× MOD, although the hairs of the outer fringe of the forebasitarsus are shorter than in the other two species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
